the way as well.

00:04:30.600 --> 00:04:37.119
But just to get started with a quick intro, I'm the head of ML Ops at Domino's.

00:04:37.119 --> 00:04:42.559
So in that capacity, my charter is to make sure that we have the right technology and

00:04:42.559 --> 00:04:50.160
process available to our data science team to be able to deploy our models into our production

00:04:50.160 --> 00:04:56.160
environments and integrate them with whatever downstream platform we're integrating with,

00:04:56.160 --> 00:05:02.399
either our e-commerce platform or in-store technology platform.

00:05:02.399 --> 00:05:06.320
My team also covers global store siting.

00:05:06.320 --> 00:05:10.640
So using geospatial data and machine learning models to identify the best places to build

00:05:10.720 --> 00:05:15.920
new Domino's stores and supply chain optimization as well.

00:05:15.920 --> 00:05:21.359
So looking across our network of stores and supply chain centers and finding ways to optimize

00:05:21.359 --> 00:05:26.320
that network to save us costs, but to also help the environment, too, which I'm really

00:05:26.320 --> 00:05:33.600
excited about that impact as well.

00:05:33.600 --> 00:05:37.480
I did want to talk about just when you talk about the Domino's data science team, like

00:05:37.480 --> 00:05:38.480
a few.

00:05:38.480 --> 00:05:39.480
Yeah.

00:05:39.480 --> 00:05:43.959
So what about something outside of work, too, before we jump in?

00:05:43.959 --> 00:05:51.200
I play guitar and I just saw Dune II last night.

00:05:51.200 --> 00:05:58.040
I finished the book over the weekend and frantically, I wanted to finish it before it got out of

00:05:58.040 --> 00:05:59.040
theaters.

00:05:59.040 --> 00:06:06.040
And I literally went to the last IMAX showing of Dune II last night at 9 p.m.

00:06:06.040 --> 00:06:14.440
So I was up until like midnight, the last IMAX before Godzilla takes over the IMAX theater

00:06:14.440 --> 00:06:15.440
near me.

00:06:15.440 --> 00:06:16.440
Nice.

00:06:16.440 --> 00:06:17.440
That's awesome.

00:06:17.440 --> 00:06:21.079
I'm working from my parents' house because I'm going to be here for Easter.

00:06:21.079 --> 00:06:24.880
And so I think my dad was about to make an appearance on the data science hangout as

00:06:24.880 --> 00:06:25.880
well.

00:06:25.880 --> 00:06:29.880
So that's why I was like waving over here.

00:06:30.880 --> 00:06:35.640
I have three kids that are home on spring break running around on the other side of

00:06:35.640 --> 00:06:36.640
that door.

00:06:36.640 --> 00:06:40.640
And I just found out the lock doesn't work, stopped working.

00:06:40.640 --> 00:06:44.239
So you might meet my kids during this as well.

00:06:44.239 --> 00:06:45.239
That's great.

00:06:45.239 --> 00:06:46.239
Awesome.

00:06:46.239 --> 00:06:52.880
Well, yeah, I'd love to learn a little bit more about the data science teams at Domino's.

00:06:52.880 --> 00:06:56.640
If you maybe can kind of share a little bit about how that's structured.

00:06:56.640 --> 00:06:58.920
Yeah, yeah.

00:06:58.959 --> 00:07:04.160
I've been lucky enough to be a part of a really exciting growth journey at Domino's.

00:07:04.160 --> 00:07:08.720
So I joined the Domino's data science team in 2018.

00:07:08.720 --> 00:07:14.160
And around that time, I think we had 10 to 15 data scientists on the team.

00:07:14.160 --> 00:07:17.959
As a team stands now, we have around 80 data scientists.

00:07:17.959 --> 00:07:24.679
So pretty rapid growth over the last few years, really focused on the business impact we've

00:07:24.679 --> 00:07:26.200
been able to deliver on.

00:07:26.480 --> 00:07:31.440
But we have 80 team members and they we have some in Seattle, we have team members in Ann

00:07:31.440 --> 00:07:34.559
Arbor, we have team members in Amsterdam, and we have team members in Singapore.

00:07:34.559 --> 00:07:41.440
So we're like truly a global data science team, which is exciting.

00:07:41.440 --> 00:07:46.320
We have some really cool partnerships, one of them being with the deposit team, which

00:07:46.320 --> 00:07:52.160
we're really excited about, but also NVIDIA and Microsoft and Docker.

00:07:52.160 --> 00:08:00.040
We have teams specializing in pricing, personalization, retail technology, store siting, forecasting,

00:08:00.040 --> 00:08:03.119
supply chain optimization, and MLOps.

00:08:03.119 --> 00:08:08.600
So cover almost every area of the business.

00:08:08.600 --> 00:08:14.880
And we have about 15 machine learning and AI models in production right now serving

00:08:14.880 --> 00:08:19.679
various business use cases.

00:08:19.679 --> 00:08:24.200
It's amazing to hear like how the team has grown to 80 people.

00:08:24.200 --> 00:08:29.720
What are some of the, I guess, takeaways or lessons learned from you and growing the team

00:08:29.720 --> 00:08:31.519
in these past few years?

00:08:31.519 --> 00:08:32.520
Wow.

00:08:32.520 --> 00:08:33.520
So many.

00:08:33.520 --> 00:08:37.719
Is that diving like too deep right from the beginning?

00:08:37.719 --> 00:08:38.719
Yeah.

00:08:38.719 --> 00:08:39.719
So many.

00:08:39.719 --> 00:08:46.119
I think if I were to give one piece of advice, you know, for someone kind of going through

00:08:46.119 --> 00:08:52.000
this journey or about to embark on this journey, it's really everything starts with the data.

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:57.679
I mean, it's so cliche now, but it's truly garbage in, garbage out.

00:08:57.679 --> 00:09:05.640
So focusing on having really high quality data that's not only exists, but is really

00:09:05.640 --> 00:09:11.960
in an accessible format for data scientists to be able to leverage to kind of extract

00:09:11.960 --> 00:09:13.599
that business value.

00:09:13.599 --> 00:09:20.200
I mean, any team that's starting, that's got to be the starting point.

00:09:20.200 --> 00:09:24.960
I see quite a few questions coming in now in the chat.

00:09:24.960 --> 00:09:28.919
And Arsenis, do you want to kick us off here with your question?

00:09:28.919 --> 00:09:30.119
Yeah.

00:09:30.119 --> 00:09:32.320
So just, you know, thanks, Rachel.

00:09:32.320 --> 00:09:38.440
So very, very quickly, just really high level to start out, I was wondering what some of

00:09:38.440 --> 00:09:44.599
the more unique challenges are in MLOps that Domino's faces.

00:09:44.599 --> 00:09:49.000
And also thank you, Zach, for joining today and taking the time for this, but yeah, that's

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:50.000
my question.

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:51.000
Thanks.

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:52.000
Of course.

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:57.400
I'm going to touch on two challenges.

00:09:57.400 --> 00:10:00.960
The first one is scalability, right?

00:10:00.960 --> 00:10:09.200
I think when you talk about ML and AI and MLOps, there's a lot that can be done on a

00:10:09.200 --> 00:10:16.359
data scientist laptop and, you know, great accuracy and recall can be achieved on models

00:10:16.359 --> 00:10:23.000
on an individual's laptop, but there's a lot of challenges that arise when trying to scale

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:27.239
that, you know, to a large system.

00:10:27.239 --> 00:10:33.919
So Domino's, maybe, probably not a shocker to anybody, but we sell a lot of pizza, you

00:10:33.919 --> 00:10:38.799
know, we sell close to a billion pizzas every year across the globe.

00:10:38.799 --> 00:10:45.080
So everything that we do has to be looked through the lens of scale.

00:10:45.080 --> 00:10:50.719
You know, there's that volume scale, but also like our business is highly concentrated,

00:10:50.719 --> 00:10:51.719
right?

00:10:51.719 --> 00:10:58.599
So if you look, you know, at the pizza business, 80% of our orders are between 5 and 7, 5 and

00:10:58.599 --> 00:10:59.599
8 p.m.

00:10:59.599 --> 00:11:05.039
And then that's on a daily level, but even if you look across the year, days like Halloween,

00:11:05.039 --> 00:11:09.760
Superbowl, New Year's, you know, represent a disproportional amount of our business.

00:11:09.760 --> 00:11:16.200
So we have to scale to be able to serve, you know, something like 6,000 orders per minute

00:11:16.200 --> 00:11:17.599
during Superbowl.

00:11:17.599 --> 00:11:23.479
So if we're doing machine learning that is kind of at the order level, our models not

00:11:23.479 --> 00:11:27.479
only need to be accurate, but performant to that scale.

00:11:27.479 --> 00:11:31.119
So that's one of the biggest challenges we face.

00:11:31.119 --> 00:11:33.440
The other one is process, right?

00:11:33.440 --> 00:11:36.840
Data scientists are experimenters at heart, right?

00:11:36.840 --> 00:11:42.320
They want to take the time to experiment with the data, experiment with different modeling

00:11:42.320 --> 00:11:47.760
types, and, you know, fitting that into a process that balances the flexibility and

00:11:47.760 --> 00:11:56.840
creativity with the control and versioning and reliability, finding the right balances

00:11:56.840 --> 00:11:58.880
is tough from a process standpoint.

00:11:58.880 --> 00:12:03.159
And that's a journey that we're still going on, to be honest.

00:12:03.159 --> 00:12:08.119
Can I add on to this question and ask, how do you address some of those challenges today?

00:12:09.119 --> 00:12:17.359
Well, many, how we address it kind of depends on the use case in terms of scalability.

00:12:17.359 --> 00:12:25.039
But, you know, we, maybe one example there is like looking at different model types and

00:12:25.039 --> 00:12:27.919
the balance between accuracy and performance.

00:12:27.919 --> 00:12:35.440
So a good example that I always go to is like, like random forests are really great at achieving

00:12:35.440 --> 00:12:41.760
accuracy, but, you know, traditionally like slow on the inferencing side.

00:12:41.760 --> 00:12:48.200
So we might make the decision to do like a deep neural net even, that might be a little

00:12:48.200 --> 00:12:55.559
bit overkill to achieve the accuracy that we need, but it's more performant from a scalability

00:12:55.559 --> 00:12:56.640
perspective.

00:12:56.640 --> 00:13:00.719
So understanding those trade-offs and having our data scientists kind of keeping that in

00:13:00.719 --> 00:13:06.719
mind as they're doing their model development experimentation is, I think, important.

00:13:06.719 --> 00:13:07.719
Yeah.

00:13:07.719 --> 00:13:08.719
Thank you.

00:13:08.719 --> 00:13:09.719
Yeah.

00:13:09.719 --> 00:13:12.719
Ralph, I see you had a question, want to jump in here next?

00:13:12.719 --> 00:13:13.719
Yeah.

00:13:13.719 --> 00:13:14.719
Zach, first things are being on here.

00:13:14.719 --> 00:13:19.520
I would probably have like a zillion questions on supply chains, but one's more broadly

00:13:19.520 --> 00:13:20.520
applicable.

00:13:20.520 --> 00:13:21.520
Sure.

00:13:21.520 --> 00:13:25.719
If you're kind of doing any sort of like very, very short-term demand forecasting, I've heard

00:13:25.719 --> 00:13:30.080
it called now, Cassie, that's what I call it, like next hour or so to try to level load

00:13:30.080 --> 00:13:31.440
demand between stores.

00:13:31.440 --> 00:13:35.239
Because like I've had a time where I've ordered it from a Domino's store nearby and they say,

00:13:35.239 --> 00:13:36.239
yeah, it's going to be two hours.

00:13:36.239 --> 00:13:38.760
And I look at the one that's a mile farther away, they're like, oh, we'll get it to you

00:13:38.760 --> 00:13:39.760
in 15 minutes.

00:13:39.760 --> 00:13:42.599
Like, it really mattered to me whether it's the closest or not.

00:13:42.599 --> 00:13:43.599
Like, yeah.

00:13:43.599 --> 00:13:47.400
I'm curious if you're doing anything like that to try to kind of improve the customer

00:13:47.400 --> 00:13:48.400
experience.

00:13:48.400 --> 00:13:50.760
Yeah, for sure.

00:13:50.760 --> 00:13:56.719
I think those are actually the areas of opportunity that we really look for because they're oftentimes

00:13:56.719 --> 00:13:57.719
a win-win.

00:13:57.719 --> 00:14:02.239
Like, when we can get the customer a hotter, fresher pizza, it's a better experience for

00:14:02.239 --> 00:14:03.239
the customer.

00:14:03.239 --> 00:14:08.960
But we can also potentially reduce the miles that we're driving on the road, improve our

00:14:08.960 --> 00:14:11.000
labor utilization rates.

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:16.840
So like, those are the kinds of efficiencies that we're kind of really after is those win-win

00:14:16.840 --> 00:14:20.359
from a customer and cost perspective.

00:14:20.960 --> 00:14:25.200
So, yeah, we look at that from several different angles.

00:14:25.200 --> 00:14:27.559
One of them is just the store siting angle.

00:14:27.559 --> 00:14:32.679
It's where do we put our stores relative to our customers to optimize our network?

00:14:32.679 --> 00:14:39.320
Domino's, we have around 6,800 stores in the United States, and that covers around 80-ish

00:14:39.320 --> 00:14:43.520
percent of the U.S. population lives in a Domino's delivery area.

00:14:43.520 --> 00:14:48.760
So we look at our stores, not as single units, but as a network of stores and how do we optimize

00:14:48.760 --> 00:14:51.119
that network to better serve our customers?

00:14:51.119 --> 00:14:55.880
So that's like at the macro level, but we're also looking at it from even a delivery routing

00:14:55.880 --> 00:14:57.159
perspective.

00:14:57.159 --> 00:15:01.400
So what orders should be grouped together on routes to better service the customers

00:15:01.400 --> 00:15:03.840
at the most micro level?

00:15:03.840 --> 00:15:04.840
Great.

00:15:04.840 --> 00:15:05.840
Thank you.

00:15:05.840 --> 00:15:06.840
Thank you.

00:15:06.840 --> 00:15:07.840
Let's see.

00:15:07.840 --> 00:15:13.640
Quite a few questions here, a few that have a star there for me to read it.

00:15:13.640 --> 00:15:16.640
So I'll ask Sam this question.

00:15:16.719 --> 00:15:22.400
Zach, has your team influenced the data collection side of things, maybe to improve data quality

00:15:22.400 --> 00:15:27.200
or to start collecting new data that previously wasn't collected?

00:15:27.200 --> 00:15:29.679
Yeah, certainly.

00:15:29.679 --> 00:15:39.280
And that is often step number one when we're embarking on a new data science or AI ML kind

00:15:39.280 --> 00:15:44.640
of project is data contract negotiation.

00:15:44.640 --> 00:15:50.559
So it kind of starts with that feature engineering, data exploration, initial model exploration

00:15:50.559 --> 00:15:57.520
phase and our data scientists kind of look at, hey, what are the most parsimonious set

00:15:57.520 --> 00:16:04.119
of features that we need to achieve the model accuracy that we're looking for?

00:16:04.119 --> 00:16:09.760
And going through that experimentation, having other data scientists review that, making

00:16:09.760 --> 00:16:13.719
sure that we're not asking for too much.

00:16:13.719 --> 00:16:18.159
Then immediately after that, and phase number two is, all right, taking that to our business

00:16:18.159 --> 00:16:19.159
partners.

00:16:19.159 --> 00:16:20.159
All right.

00:16:20.159 --> 00:16:26.200
And that includes our enterprise data warehouse team that includes like our e-commerce team

00:16:26.200 --> 00:16:30.039
or in-store platform team and saying, hey, this is the model we want to build and this

00:16:30.039 --> 00:16:35.799
is the data that we're going to need to kind of service that model at inference.

00:16:35.799 --> 00:16:36.799
And then it becomes a negotiation.

00:16:37.599 --> 00:16:42.400
And we literally call it like data contract negotiation between the partners.

00:16:42.400 --> 00:16:44.880
So and there's gives and takes, right?

00:16:44.880 --> 00:16:50.080
Because every data, especially when you're talking about real-time inferencing, right?

00:16:50.080 --> 00:16:52.760
Passing data, there's a real cost to it.

00:16:52.760 --> 00:16:58.280
So taking those things into consideration, balancing that with what's needed to achieve

00:16:58.280 --> 00:17:05.920
a certain level of accuracy is a big part of the initial planning for any project we

00:17:05.920 --> 00:17:06.920
have.

00:17:06.920 --> 00:17:07.920
Thank you.

00:17:07.920 --> 00:17:15.520
I wanted to make sure we get a minute to talk about the local meetup that you want to start

00:17:15.520 --> 00:17:16.520
as well.

00:17:16.520 --> 00:17:21.560
Because I've been thinking about, and I had a note to mention this, but like the Boston

00:17:21.560 --> 00:17:26.880
Usar group is pretty much sponsored by like having Domino's pizza and thinking of how

00:17:26.880 --> 00:17:34.079
many meetups around the world and how many data scientists get together and like how often

00:17:34.239 --> 00:17:36.560
Domino's is involved in that.

00:17:36.560 --> 00:17:38.959
And I know you wanted to start a group too.

00:17:38.959 --> 00:17:42.239
So just had to take a few minutes to chat a little bit about that.

00:17:42.239 --> 00:17:49.280
Yeah, first of all, like if it's not already obvious, I've totally drank the Domino's Kool-Aid.

00:17:49.280 --> 00:17:54.319
So just like bear with me, but you know, that is like the cool thing about working for Domino's

00:17:54.319 --> 00:17:57.160
is like at the service level, it's just a pizza company.

00:17:57.160 --> 00:18:03.479
But when you realize like the magic of pizza and it's like what you have at your kid's

00:18:03.479 --> 00:18:09.920
birthday party, it's what you have at a data science users meetup, it's, you know, the

00:18:09.920 --> 00:18:15.160
night at home watching a movie, you know, with your significant other, it's those like

00:18:15.160 --> 00:18:20.219
kind of cool moments that I think are what make Domino's special.

00:18:20.219 --> 00:18:27.520
So that's my obligatory PR statement, or not so obligatory actually.

00:18:28.520 --> 00:18:36.040
So yeah, I think in that spirit, like this is me doing this as kind of a step one for

00:18:36.040 --> 00:18:40.560
something that our data science leadership team has been talking about is like how do

00:18:40.560 --> 00:18:48.239
we engage the data science community and give back to the community and like the spirit

00:18:48.239 --> 00:18:55.119
of, you know, rising seas raise all ships and like working together and building collaborations

00:18:55.119 --> 00:18:56.119
outside Domino's.

00:18:56.119 --> 00:19:03.319
So we're looking at ways to do that, you know, one of them is, you know, hosting our own

00:19:03.319 --> 00:19:05.119
user group in the Ann Arbor area.

00:19:05.119 --> 00:19:09.000
So if any of you guys are interested, please reach out, we're in the very early stages

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:13.160
of potentially planning something like that.

