Yeah, if anybody's in the area, Ann Arbor, comment in the chat.

00:19:23.760 --> 00:19:29.920
I'd also be happy to help connect with people that I know in the area too.

00:19:29.920 --> 00:19:33.839
I see Alan, you asked a question in the chat, want to jump in here next?

00:19:33.839 --> 00:19:34.839
Yeah, sure.

00:19:34.839 --> 00:19:35.839
Hi, Zack.

00:19:35.839 --> 00:19:36.839
Hi, everybody.

00:19:36.839 --> 00:19:41.119
I think Zack, your answer to Sam's question really overlapped with a lot of the stuff

00:19:41.119 --> 00:19:46.439
I was interested in about the partnership and how you may have to influence like stakeholders

00:19:46.439 --> 00:19:49.560
to get to consensus about what to do.

00:19:49.680 --> 00:19:57.000
I'll reframe it a tiny bit and say I'm curious, like as you get requests or projects, is there

00:19:57.000 --> 00:20:01.680
like a product champion or a product specialist or something like, is there someone who kind

00:20:01.680 --> 00:20:06.000
of owns it from end to end, who's really responsible for conceptualization?

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:13.000
Or do you get like work from all over the place, which means you've got like 15 funnels

00:20:13.000 --> 00:20:17.640
kind of coming towards you that you've got to prioritize and manage and stuff?

00:20:17.719 --> 00:20:23.959
Yeah, I can sense like where that question is coming from and I just want to know, like

00:20:23.959 --> 00:20:26.880
I feel you at the same wavelength.

00:20:26.880 --> 00:20:34.560
So yeah, that is a challenge and I don't know, maybe for, at the risk of giving you an unanswered,

00:20:34.560 --> 00:20:37.760
I think it's like really striking that balance.

00:20:37.760 --> 00:20:46.000
One of the things that really I love about Domino's culture is the entrepreneur, like

00:20:46.040 --> 00:20:48.199
entrepreneurial nature of it, right?

00:20:48.199 --> 00:20:54.000
So the fact that ideas can come from anywhere, any department, any level, and like those

00:20:54.000 --> 00:21:00.800
ideas have a real shot at making it into like a product that, or a project that, you know,

00:21:00.800 --> 00:21:06.079
gets to be seen by the world if it's a marketing window or a piece of technology that gets

00:21:06.079 --> 00:21:11.280
to be experienced by hundreds of millions of Domino's customers all over the globe.

00:21:11.280 --> 00:21:13.640
So that's really exciting.

00:21:13.640 --> 00:21:21.319
But the double-edged sword to that is, you know, it can be kind of chaotic and, you know,

00:21:21.319 --> 00:21:29.479
keeping the reins in and prioritization then become really paramount.

00:21:29.479 --> 00:21:36.400
So having a process for taking in those really great ideas, prioritizing them, and then to

00:21:36.439 --> 00:21:43.079
your point, assigning a champion or a product owner that can be kind of responsible for that.

00:21:43.079 --> 00:21:52.520
And, you know, one of the ways we're kind of addressing that now, which is really we're

00:21:52.520 --> 00:21:58.239
trying it out, is taking more of that product owner approach, like borrowing from Agile

00:21:58.239 --> 00:22:03.959
and really having product data science, product owners that aren't necessarily data scientists

00:22:03.959 --> 00:22:10.119
or have expertise in AI or ML, but are really good at project management and seeing a project

00:22:10.119 --> 00:22:15.479
through from end to end and can supplement, you know, that skill set with our data scientists

00:22:15.479 --> 00:22:20.839
who are, you know, have that creativity and technical orientation.

00:22:20.839 --> 00:22:29.839
So that's kind of an area that we're exploring to address, you know, this topic you're bringing up.

00:22:29.839 --> 00:22:30.839
Super. Thank you.

00:22:30.839 --> 00:22:33.119
Yeah, sounds like familiar dilemmas.

00:22:33.119 --> 00:22:38.119
And it sounds like you've got the organization sounds like it's really well positioned to

00:22:38.119 --> 00:22:41.119
have support to figure that stuff out, which is really cool.

00:22:41.119 --> 00:22:42.119
Yep.

00:22:42.119 --> 00:22:43.119
Thanks.

00:22:43.119 --> 00:22:45.880
You know, sometimes you experiment with models.

00:22:45.880 --> 00:22:48.800
Sometimes you got to experiment with process, too.

00:22:48.800 --> 00:22:52.280
So I think that we're open to that as well.

00:22:52.280 --> 00:22:56.520
I see Arthi had a question a little bit earlier.

00:22:56.800 --> 00:23:01.920
Do you have data science models used for supply chain analytics, like the quantity of ingredients

00:23:01.920 --> 00:23:07.599
needed by a store and how to make sure they don't run out, especially on high demand days?

00:23:07.599 --> 00:23:08.599
Yeah.

00:23:08.599 --> 00:23:17.040
So really, when I think about or at least the level of technicality I can speak to on

00:23:17.040 --> 00:23:23.959
this topic, I think about kind of two different flavors of model that we implement to optimize

00:23:23.959 --> 00:23:26.280
our supply chain network.

00:23:27.040 --> 00:23:28.040
I think one is forecasting.

00:23:28.040 --> 00:23:29.040
Right.

00:23:29.040 --> 00:23:32.000
That's that's kind of key to all of this.

00:23:32.000 --> 00:23:36.239
When you're talking about optimizing supply chain, it's not because we want to you know,

00:23:36.239 --> 00:23:39.160
we can't fix anything that already happened.

00:23:39.160 --> 00:23:41.760
So we want to optimize into the future.

00:23:41.760 --> 00:23:46.719
So that kind of necessitates those time series forecasting models.

00:23:46.719 --> 00:23:53.000
And we kind of have a whole laundry basket of forecasting models that we implement at

00:23:53.040 --> 00:24:01.160
the, you know, from the hourly demand signature level to the store level, to the system level,

00:24:01.160 --> 00:24:03.800
we look at forecasting.

00:24:03.800 --> 00:24:12.439
And then really the where the the next step of that is really then combining that with

00:24:12.439 --> 00:24:15.599
more combinatorial optimization algorithms.

00:24:15.599 --> 00:24:17.239
Right.

00:24:17.239 --> 00:24:22.839
So not even like traditional AI or ML, but things like mixed integer programs, right,

00:24:22.839 --> 00:24:26.599
or vehicle routing solvers, right.

00:24:26.599 --> 00:24:32.599
And one of the cool things that we're doing in that area is, again, to address like the

00:24:32.599 --> 00:24:39.640
earlier topic of scalability, traditional like MIP or vehicle routing solvers, they're

00:24:39.640 --> 00:24:44.319
meant to solve logistics problems like overnight, because like orders come in, and then the

00:24:44.400 --> 00:24:48.640
next day, you need trucks, and they take the whole day to deliver those routes, and then

00:24:48.640 --> 00:24:50.640
they come back to this depot.

00:24:50.640 --> 00:24:58.640
Well, for us, like, we need to route delivery drivers, they're taking, you know, 1000 routes

00:24:58.640 --> 00:25:01.119
a minute when you look across our entire system.

00:25:01.119 --> 00:25:04.680
So we need to solve those vehicle routing problems really fast.

00:25:04.680 --> 00:25:09.959
So we've partnered with Nvidia to leverage their coop solver, which is that is really

00:25:09.959 --> 00:25:16.839
cool with the first GPU enabled vehicle routing solver, and it's able to solve those problems

00:25:16.839 --> 00:25:23.000
really fast and get to almost the very, very close to the ideal solution.

00:25:25.319 --> 00:25:25.560
Cool.

00:25:26.280 --> 00:25:27.160
Thank you for sharing.

00:25:27.800 --> 00:25:28.119
I see.

00:25:29.640 --> 00:25:32.839
Runwa, you had a question a little bit earlier, you want to jump in?

00:25:36.760 --> 00:25:39.160
I think it was around communicating messy data.

00:25:39.959 --> 00:25:41.160
To business stakeholders.

00:25:42.680 --> 00:25:45.400
I can ask and if you want to add more context, feel free.

00:25:46.359 --> 00:25:53.000
But it was, is there a better way to communicate to leadership or business stakeholders about

00:25:53.000 --> 00:25:57.959
most of the data being messy and just deal with it and build a model and get something

00:25:57.959 --> 00:25:58.920
from messy data?

00:25:59.479 --> 00:26:03.560
Usually 60 to 80% of data science time is data wrangling.

00:26:03.560 --> 00:26:06.680
However, leadership may want to cut this time.

00:26:06.680 --> 00:26:07.640
What do you think?

00:26:07.640 --> 00:26:08.599
Any thoughts to share?

00:26:10.839 --> 00:26:11.319
Hmm.

00:26:13.000 --> 00:26:17.959
Man, I see both sides of this coin, to be honest with you.

00:26:17.959 --> 00:26:18.359
Right.

00:26:18.359 --> 00:26:23.479
And which I think is probably is at the root of what makes this a challenging problem.

00:26:24.280 --> 00:26:24.520
Right.

00:26:25.640 --> 00:26:28.920
You have what I talked about earlier, garbage in, garbage out.

00:26:28.920 --> 00:26:29.239
Right.

00:26:29.239 --> 00:26:34.280
Like the accuracy of your model, which I'll use as like a pseudonym for value.

00:26:34.280 --> 00:26:34.839
Right.

00:26:34.839 --> 00:26:38.040
Assuming more accuracy is more value.

00:26:38.040 --> 00:26:38.280
Right.

00:26:39.319 --> 00:26:43.239
The data going in that you have available, whether it's messy or even the scope of the

00:26:43.239 --> 00:26:48.439
data, like what you have is clean, but you're missing key pieces of information.

00:26:51.000 --> 00:26:52.520
That impacts your accuracy.

00:26:52.520 --> 00:26:58.119
And it's going to therefore limit the amount of value in some cases that you can deliver

00:26:58.119 --> 00:26:58.760
on.

00:26:58.760 --> 00:27:06.520
On the other side of that coin is leadership has a point that says like, hey, we're not

00:27:06.520 --> 00:27:11.000
looking for the maximum amount of accuracy that we can see from your model.

00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:14.680
We believe that there's value in a lower accuracy model.

00:27:15.319 --> 00:27:22.920
And I think the answer to this question kind of lies in establishing a baseline and really

00:27:22.920 --> 00:27:26.599
understanding what you're trying to what you're trying to beat.

00:27:27.880 --> 00:27:30.599
In most cases, it's like a human decision.

00:27:30.599 --> 00:27:31.000
Right.

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:37.400
Or a very basic, like more like algebra type problem.

00:27:37.400 --> 00:27:40.280
Like, for example, our delivery times.

00:27:41.239 --> 00:27:41.560
Right.

00:27:41.560 --> 00:27:43.800
One simple way to look at our delivery times.

00:27:43.800 --> 00:27:48.599
If we didn't have if we didn't know how many drivers were available, how many people were

00:27:48.599 --> 00:27:54.920
working in our store, we didn't know information about the order or all the orders ahead of

00:27:54.920 --> 00:27:55.719
it on the make line.

00:27:55.719 --> 00:28:01.800
If we didn't have all of that, we could still the baseline model is just a look at the stores

00:28:01.800 --> 00:28:02.839
last 20 minutes.

00:28:02.839 --> 00:28:05.319
What was their average delivery time and just use that.

00:28:06.439 --> 00:28:06.760
Right.

00:28:06.760 --> 00:28:12.439
So knowing that that's the baseline kind of helps you have that target.

00:28:12.439 --> 00:28:20.040
And then you can say, hey, we either do or don't have the data that we need to perform

00:28:20.040 --> 00:28:21.800
better than whatever that baseline is.

00:28:22.599 --> 00:28:26.280
I think that's maybe something that is more tangible to leadership.

00:28:27.079 --> 00:28:29.479
Hey, what we want to do is perform better than this.

00:28:30.119 --> 00:28:35.800
And, you know, we are not able to create a minimum viable model that that overcomes that

00:28:35.800 --> 00:28:37.160
based on the data that we have.

00:28:39.880 --> 00:28:41.319
Thank you, Jared.

00:28:41.319 --> 00:28:44.119
I see you have two questions that maybe kind of go together.

00:28:44.119 --> 00:28:45.640
Do you want to jump in here and ask those?

00:28:49.800 --> 00:28:50.359
Yeah, sorry.

00:28:51.079 --> 00:28:56.680
Well, the first one is kind of like ROI is always a big conversation when we're talking

00:28:56.680 --> 00:29:01.959
about any projects, especially when you're trying to, you know, at the strategic level,

00:29:01.959 --> 00:29:03.719
try to which ones had the priority.

00:29:04.439 --> 00:29:10.680
And I think the other one was is more from a kind of metrics perspective of the data is

00:29:10.680 --> 00:29:17.319
do you what amount of external data thinking like whether any kind of stuff you would use

00:29:17.319 --> 00:29:21.880
outside of the company is the mix between internal versus external data were much of

00:29:21.880 --> 00:29:22.439
the questions.

00:29:23.800 --> 00:29:24.199
Got it.

00:29:25.400 --> 00:29:32.920
Yeah, I think one of the skills that I had to develop as I transitioned from

00:29:35.959 --> 00:29:41.000
individual contributor data scientist to senior data scientist to people leader in

00:29:41.000 --> 00:29:46.760
the data science space is being really, really good at capturing the value chain.

00:29:48.040 --> 00:29:48.280
Right.

00:29:49.479 --> 00:29:54.680
Because in data science, you might not be doing the thing that then immediately impacts

00:29:54.680 --> 00:29:55.800
the business value.

00:29:55.800 --> 00:29:58.680
Like you might be doing something two rungs down.

00:29:58.680 --> 00:30:04.199
And I'll just like bring up the delivery time estimate as an example.

00:30:04.760 --> 00:30:05.160
Right.

00:30:05.160 --> 00:30:11.160
Like, why does giving a customer a better delivery time estimate?

00:30:11.160 --> 00:30:12.839
Why is that valuable to Domino's?

00:30:14.439 --> 00:30:14.920
Right.

00:30:14.920 --> 00:30:19.319
Well, if they get a better estimate, like we're more likely to meet their expectations.

00:30:19.319 --> 00:30:22.680
If we meet their expectations, they're more likely to order more pizza.

00:30:22.680 --> 00:30:25.400
If they order more pizza, then the company makes more money.

00:30:25.400 --> 00:30:27.560
That's like a really stupid, simple example.

00:30:27.560 --> 00:30:32.599
But like that can get really complex depending on what your business is.

00:30:32.599 --> 00:30:37.880
So being really good at illustrating and capturing that value chain,

00:30:39.479 --> 00:30:42.520
I think is an important skill to develop.

00:30:42.680 --> 00:30:44.520
And it's kind of an art and a science.

00:30:47.319 --> 00:30:50.839
The other question was on mix of internal and external data.

00:30:53.640 --> 00:31:00.439
I feel very fortunate at Domino's that we have a really, you know, what I think of as

00:31:00.439 --> 00:31:07.000
a really well curated data science mart, where we have access to a lot of information about

00:31:07.400 --> 00:31:12.520
a lot of information about our stores, our orders, our customers.

00:31:13.479 --> 00:31:19.239
And it's really in not perfect, but it's in a very good place in terms of like

00:31:19.239 --> 00:31:21.479
accessibility to our data science team.

00:31:21.479 --> 00:31:27.079
So the amount that we have to look at third party data is not huge.

00:31:27.079 --> 00:31:31.479
So it's definitely primarily we're looking at Domino's own data.

00:31:31.479 --> 00:31:34.599
But there are certainly areas where you look for third party data.

00:31:34.599 --> 00:31:38.599
You know, on the store siting team, I purchased geospatial demographic data.

00:31:39.959 --> 00:31:44.920
So understanding where, you know, what are not our customers look like and where are

00:31:44.920 --> 00:31:48.520
they located and information about them.

00:31:49.160 --> 00:31:56.119
We also purchased like credit card data, weather data, event based data.

00:31:57.400 --> 00:32:03.959
So I would say predominantly Domino's, but certainly we bring in third party in certain

00:32:03.959 --> 00:32:04.459
cases.

00:32:06.599 --> 00:32:07.099
Thank you.

00:32:08.280 --> 00:32:12.680
Joseph had a question earlier that was, you mentioned a lot of different areas of the

00:32:12.680 --> 00:32:18.280
business that the team touches, but has anybody applied data science techniques to recipe

00:32:18.280 --> 00:32:21.319
development or any A-B testing there?

00:32:23.560 --> 00:32:25.560
No, that's really cool, honestly.

00:32:26.359 --> 00:32:31.560
So certainly our research science team is involved in, you know, consumer research around

00:32:31.560 --> 00:32:37.319
new products and yeah, anything that we, if you notice like Domino's doesn't take like

00:32:37.319 --> 00:32:42.119
a limited time offer approach where we're like, you know, putting out things and testing

00:32:42.119 --> 00:32:42.760
them like that.

00:32:43.560 --> 00:32:49.000
We really put a lot of effort into our product research and like really ensuring if we're

00:32:49.000 --> 00:32:54.680
going to release a new product that it's going to be a creative to the business and it's

00:32:54.680 --> 00:32:57.479
going to be well received by customers.

00:32:58.280 --> 00:33:05.400
So we're not like, we're not the brand to be putting out new products all the time, but

00:33:05.400 --> 00:33:10.359
when we do, they usually do really well because we do a lot of research ahead of time.

00:33:11.000 --> 00:33:19.079
Now, this is like a really cool, fun, like LLM case study, I think is like, hey, if we

00:33:19.079 --> 00:33:24.760
looked at generative AI, like what kind of crazy pizzas or products could we generate

00:33:24.760 --> 00:33:25.719
from AI?

00:33:25.719 --> 00:33:28.839
That sounds like a fun one that kind of sparked my thinking on that.

00:33:29.719 --> 00:33:32.920
I see a lot of people volunteering to test pizza.

00:33:34.680 --> 00:33:35.880
You're in the Ann Arbor area.

00:33:35.880 --> 00:33:39.239
We do have product testing panels that are open to the public.

00:33:39.239 --> 00:33:40.760
So shoot me a message.

00:33:40.760 --> 00:33:42.119
I can get you added to the list.

00:33:42.760 --> 00:33:43.319
Oh, cool.

00:33:44.920 --> 00:33:46.439
Greg, you just put a question in the chat.

00:33:46.439 --> 00:33:47.079
Want to go next?

00:33:49.800 --> 00:33:50.439
Yeah, absolutely.

00:33:50.439 --> 00:33:50.760
Thank you.

00:33:51.319 --> 00:33:53.400
First of all, thanks for being here, too.

00:33:53.400 --> 00:33:59.079
And thank you for introducing the pizza tracker, because outside of people comparing their

00:33:59.079 --> 00:34:05.000
product to Uber, that's the second that I hear is, can we build a Domino's pizza tracker

00:34:05.000 --> 00:34:07.880
for our data pipeline or something like that?

00:34:07.880 --> 00:34:13.800
So I used to work in telecom, and so we did a little bit of supply chain as well.

00:34:13.800 --> 00:34:15.399
We did like field measurement.

00:34:15.479 --> 00:34:20.520
And so I was wondering how closely your team partners with the folks that are in the field,

00:34:20.520 --> 00:34:25.560
whether it be the stores, the drivers, whoever it might be, to observe some of the creation

00:34:25.560 --> 00:34:28.840
of your data, because that's something that we found very insightful.

00:34:28.840 --> 00:34:35.080
Sometimes we saw things, like you talked about delivery duration or time, and we found lots

00:34:35.080 --> 00:34:40.919
of different ways that people could kind of, I don't want to say game the system, but change

00:34:41.879 --> 00:34:45.560
the creation of the data in a way that we weren't expecting.

00:34:47.159 --> 00:34:56.120
Yeah, this is like one of the pieces of culture that really excites me about Domino's.

00:34:56.120 --> 00:35:01.000
Everybody that works for Domino's corporate offices knows how to make a pizza.

00:35:01.000 --> 00:35:03.879
So we have a program called Pizza Prep School.

00:35:03.879 --> 00:35:10.280
So when you're onboarded into the company, you participate, and we literally have a fully

00:35:10.360 --> 00:35:14.439
functioning Domino's store in the center of our world headquarters.

00:35:14.439 --> 00:35:15.800
It has glass all around it.

00:35:15.800 --> 00:35:18.919
You can see it from anywhere in the building.

00:35:18.919 --> 00:35:24.760
And when you're onboarded, you get with your onboarding group, and you run that store for

00:35:24.760 --> 00:35:25.560
a week.

00:35:25.560 --> 00:35:27.320
So, and that's everything.

00:35:27.320 --> 00:35:33.000
You take orders, you do delivery, because people in the corporate office can order pizza

00:35:33.000 --> 00:35:35.959
to their desk, you know, to take home with them or to have for lunch.

00:35:36.520 --> 00:35:40.360
You make, you know, you spread the dough, you sauce, you cheese.

00:35:40.919 --> 00:35:43.159
There's even a bubble popper position.

00:35:43.159 --> 00:35:48.679
So watching the oven and popping the bubbles as the pizza goes to the oven, and washing

00:35:48.679 --> 00:35:49.399
dishes.

00:35:49.399 --> 00:35:51.719
Like you do everything in that week.

00:35:52.280 --> 00:36:01.000
And yeah, everyone from our CEO down, you know, to the lowest level team member knows

00:36:01.000 --> 00:36:02.360
how to make a pizza.

00:36:03.159 --> 00:36:06.600
Luckily, the CEO is better at running a company than making pizza.

00:36:08.679 --> 00:36:13.719
But yeah, that's something that's really infused into the culture of Domino's is that operations

00:36:13.719 --> 00:36:15.639
mindset and like boots on the ground.

00:36:17.479 --> 00:36:18.040
Absolutely.

00:36:18.679 --> 00:36:24.679
Rachel, if we ever do a data science hangout in person, I think we've found our location.

00:36:24.679 --> 00:36:25.959
I know, absolutely.

00:36:26.679 --> 00:36:28.280
I think that's how this started, Zach.

00:36:28.280 --> 00:36:30.679
Weren't you offering to do a hangout in person?

00:36:31.159 --> 00:36:33.080
I'm, the offer stands.

00:36:33.080 --> 00:36:34.199
Let's figure it out.

00:36:34.199 --> 00:36:35.879
Okay, we'll figure it out.

00:36:38.280 --> 00:36:40.600
I see Ross asked a question a bit earlier.

00:36:40.600 --> 00:36:41.159
I'll read it.

00:36:41.159 --> 00:36:44.520
It was, what is the most important measure in the business?

00:36:44.520 --> 00:36:47.560
And what is most predictive of that measure?

00:36:49.399 --> 00:36:50.360
Oh, my God.

00:36:51.399 --> 00:36:55.159
This is a hard one.

00:36:56.280 --> 00:36:59.399
Well, it's funny because it shouldn't be hard.

00:37:00.360 --> 00:37:10.199
So I will, depending on who you ask in the company, you might get a slightly different

00:37:10.199 --> 00:37:10.760
answer.

00:37:10.760 --> 00:37:15.159
Both of them are related, but slightly different.

00:37:15.719 --> 00:37:21.320
So one group would tell you that it's pizza sales.

00:37:22.600 --> 00:37:24.600
That one's pretty obvious, right?

00:37:24.600 --> 00:37:27.320
Sell more pizza, make more money.

00:37:27.320 --> 00:37:28.439
More money is good.

00:37:28.439 --> 00:37:30.360
Investors like that, funny enough.

00:37:32.040 --> 00:37:39.239
But the other group, because this is FYI, like Domino's is a franchise model, right?

00:37:39.239 --> 00:37:47.959
So of that 6,800 stores that I mentioned, 99% of them are franchise owned.

00:37:47.959 --> 00:37:54.199
So I think we own like 200 or 300 corporate stores out of that 6,800.

00:37:54.840 --> 00:38:01.320
So some people might say, hey, our customer is actually the franchisee and our key metric

00:38:01.320 --> 00:38:03.639
for success is franchisee profitability.

00:38:04.199 --> 00:38:13.000
More profitable franchisees, more stores get open, more royalties come through, the more

00:38:13.000 --> 00:38:13.879
money that we make.

00:38:14.840 --> 00:38:20.439
So to get to your point on what are the correlates, right?

00:38:20.439 --> 00:38:24.360
This is where herein lies some of the gray area, right?

00:38:24.360 --> 00:38:30.199
Because if we're trying to maximize franchisee profitability, of course, pizza sales are

00:38:30.199 --> 00:38:31.320
related to that.

00:38:31.320 --> 00:38:35.399
But having more efficient operations, right?

00:38:35.399 --> 00:38:40.280
And cost savings also kind of play into that equation.

00:38:40.280 --> 00:38:46.600
So when you look at it from that lens, the operational efficiency and reducing the cost

00:38:46.600 --> 00:38:52.439
for franchisees to open a new store and to operate a new store become really critical.

00:38:54.439 --> 00:39:01.479
So that's my long-winded answer to your should be straightforward question.

00:39:01.479 --> 00:39:02.520
Oh, that's great.

00:39:02.520 --> 00:39:08.280
I see Rick actually had a follow-up on how it works with the franchisees.

00:39:08.280 --> 00:39:11.560
And it was, are the franchisees supported by your team?

00:39:11.560 --> 00:39:15.719
And if so, do they receive the same level of service as a company-owned store?

00:39:17.239 --> 00:39:18.840
And yeah, I'll stop there.

00:39:19.719 --> 00:39:25.959
This is getting into some nuance of the business, but the answer is yes.

00:39:25.959 --> 00:39:33.159
So franchisees pay royalties on the sales of their pizza.

00:39:33.159 --> 00:39:36.439
That kind of goes back to the corporate general coffers.

00:39:36.439 --> 00:39:38.919
But they also pay a technology fee.

00:39:39.800 --> 00:39:45.479
So data science also kind of operates in that capacity as well.

00:39:46.679 --> 00:39:52.679
Kind of servicing them through providing them with better technology.

00:39:53.239 --> 00:39:58.760
So that's kind of the connection in the charter that we have with our franchisees.

00:40:01.000 --> 00:40:01.479
Thank you.

00:40:02.600 --> 00:40:06.600
I see Sally asked a question, but she had to drop for another meeting.

00:40:06.600 --> 00:40:11.560
But the question was, what languages are your teams using for MLOps work?

00:40:11.560 --> 00:40:14.600
And what tools are you using to help with those workflows?

00:40:17.159 --> 00:40:17.879
Yes.

00:40:17.879 --> 00:40:24.280
So I want to say I am not a programming language Nazi.

00:40:24.280 --> 00:40:31.719
So I think we try to be open and flexible to the languages that team members want to use.

00:40:32.439 --> 00:40:41.159
That being said, we've kind of landed on Python as our production software language.

00:40:41.800 --> 00:40:46.600
And really, the decision was made early on to kind of standardize on one language for

00:40:46.600 --> 00:40:48.280
our production level work.

00:40:49.800 --> 00:40:59.320
Just from an efficiency standpoint, getting the right, creating that reviewer, having

00:40:59.320 --> 00:41:05.399
reviewers reviewing one language, not multiple languages, and not having to write two sets

00:41:05.399 --> 00:41:07.560
of documentation for everything that we're doing.

00:41:08.520 --> 00:41:15.000
It was a really practical decision to kind of land on one language for the production

00:41:15.000 --> 00:41:15.639
stuff.

00:41:15.639 --> 00:41:24.760
But in terms of like R&D experimentation, data wrangling, we are customers of PositConnect.

00:41:24.760 --> 00:41:28.840
So even like some web app type development, we do an R.

00:41:32.280 --> 00:41:32.600
Cool.

00:41:33.479 --> 00:41:37.560
I mean, we all love hearing these pizza use cases.

00:41:37.560 --> 00:41:43.080
Could you maybe share one of your favorite use cases of the team?

00:41:43.080 --> 00:41:43.639
Oh, yeah.

00:41:45.000 --> 00:41:46.040
This one's pretty easy.

00:41:47.399 --> 00:41:52.520
And unfortunately, like it's an older use case.

00:41:52.520 --> 00:41:56.840
So like, but still my favorite.

00:41:57.399 --> 00:42:02.120
It was the Points for Pie program that launched in 2019.

00:42:02.760 --> 00:42:10.679
And if you guys didn't see it or don't remember what it was, was we would give you Domino's

00:42:10.679 --> 00:42:13.800
loyalty points for any pizza that you ordered.

00:42:13.800 --> 00:42:15.399
Didn't have to be Domino's pizza.

00:42:16.040 --> 00:42:21.719
And how you redeemed those points was you would go into our app and you would scan your

00:42:21.719 --> 00:42:22.439
pizza.

00:42:22.439 --> 00:42:31.399
So we built a pizza, not pizza model to detect whether that pizza was present and then you

00:42:31.399 --> 00:42:36.520
would get the points for loyalty points for that pizza.

00:42:36.520 --> 00:42:39.080
So that's one of my favorites.

00:42:39.080 --> 00:42:40.120
Got really good PR.

00:42:41.560 --> 00:42:45.639
Not everything that we do as data scientists gets to end up in a marketing window that

00:42:45.639 --> 00:42:47.560
gets seen by everybody.

00:42:47.560 --> 00:42:50.600
So that was a really cool opportunity.

00:42:52.840 --> 00:42:53.399
That's funny.

00:42:54.280 --> 00:42:55.800
How did that idea come to life?

00:42:55.800 --> 00:42:57.719
Or where did the idea first come from?

00:42:57.719 --> 00:43:00.520
I don't know if I got it directly from Silicon Valley.

00:43:02.760 --> 00:43:05.719
They built like the hot dog, not hot dog model or something like that.

00:43:06.439 --> 00:43:11.560
I don't know if that's how it was sparked, but I like to think that it was.

00:43:15.719 --> 00:43:17.080
Donald, I see you had a question.

00:43:17.080 --> 00:43:17.719
Want to go next?

00:43:17.719 --> 00:43:23.000
Donald, I can read it.

00:43:24.760 --> 00:43:25.560
Can you hear me?

00:43:25.560 --> 00:43:26.120
Yep.

00:43:26.120 --> 00:43:26.679
Okay, great.

00:43:26.679 --> 00:43:27.159
Yeah.

00:43:27.159 --> 00:43:28.199
Thank you, Rachel.

00:43:28.199 --> 00:43:28.439
Yeah.

00:43:28.439 --> 00:43:34.280
So a lot of times when I put models into production, I have to get a lot of buy-in in order to

00:43:34.280 --> 00:43:39.719
do any type of extra validation afterwards, like relabeling a random set of cases every

00:43:39.719 --> 00:43:43.000
quarter to make sure there's no drift assessment.

00:43:43.560 --> 00:43:49.560
Have you had any difficulties doing any type of drift assessment or any type of reanalyzing

00:43:49.560 --> 00:43:51.399
of the performance after production?

00:43:55.479 --> 00:43:58.919
This is a big area of opportunity for our team.

00:44:00.199 --> 00:44:08.040
I think we do do kind of model accuracy assessment and we get daily.

00:44:08.840 --> 00:44:15.719
The whoever data science team kind of owns that production model is kind of responsible

00:44:15.719 --> 00:44:24.919
for monitoring that model accuracy and flagging any drift that they see in our ability to

00:44:24.919 --> 00:44:25.719
make predictions.

00:44:27.800 --> 00:44:35.719
And we do have some cool use cases of detecting anomalies.

00:44:35.719 --> 00:44:41.639
So for example, like with our delivery time estimation model, this just happened recently.

00:44:43.159 --> 00:44:51.399
There's a new manager in one of the stores and he switched everyone's position code to

00:44:51.399 --> 00:44:51.879
driver.

00:44:53.800 --> 00:45:00.120
So I don't know if it was easy for him or whatever to do that, but we started giving

00:45:00.120 --> 00:45:04.439
really, really fast delivery time estimates for that store and they're like wildly inaccurate.

00:45:05.080 --> 00:45:12.280
The customers were getting pizzas in like an hour or something and we would say that

00:45:12.280 --> 00:45:13.639
they were going to be there in five minutes.

00:45:14.840 --> 00:45:15.239
Crazy.

00:45:15.239 --> 00:45:18.199
So we shut down the model for that store.

00:45:18.199 --> 00:45:20.439
We turned the flag off for that store.

00:45:20.439 --> 00:45:22.360
So there's stories like that.

00:45:22.919 --> 00:45:30.360
But where I want to take us from the leadership perspective on this group is really creating

00:45:30.360 --> 00:45:36.760
that single pane of glass where we can have like, I almost think of like the command center

00:45:36.760 --> 00:45:42.679
Star Trek kind of thing that is like, hey, this is my control panel for all my machine

00:45:42.679 --> 00:45:48.199
learning models that are in production and kind of being able to assess just the general

00:45:48.199 --> 00:45:49.879
health of the service.

00:45:49.879 --> 00:45:51.159
Like, is it up and running?

00:45:51.159 --> 00:45:53.479
Is the throughput what we expected?

00:45:53.479 --> 00:45:56.679
But also like, is the data coming in what we expected?

00:45:56.679 --> 00:45:58.840
And is the accuracy what we expected?

00:45:58.840 --> 00:46:04.520
So we can like land there and say, you know, hey, Model X, Y, Z, is it green health?

00:46:04.520 --> 00:46:06.040
Model Y is yellow.

00:46:06.040 --> 00:46:07.399
We need to look into that.

00:46:07.399 --> 00:46:09.959
And then Model Z is red.

00:46:09.959 --> 00:46:11.320
We need to shut that down right now.

00:46:12.280 --> 00:46:15.719
So that's my dream, my vision.

00:46:16.439 --> 00:46:19.000
Making that a reality is on the road map.

00:46:23.000 --> 00:46:26.840
It looks like we successfully sold one Domino's pizza right now.

00:46:26.840 --> 00:46:30.120
Nessa is ordering a pizza right now, just so you know.

00:46:31.399 --> 00:46:33.320
Get the pan, okay?

00:46:33.320 --> 00:46:35.239
Pan pizza, that's where it's at.

00:46:36.280 --> 00:46:39.800
Hand tossed is great, but you know, treat yourself.

00:46:39.800 --> 00:46:40.520
You deserve it.

00:46:40.520 --> 00:46:41.000
Get the pan.

00:46:44.360 --> 00:46:47.800
Going back to, I think it was Sally's question.

00:46:47.800 --> 00:46:52.120
Bill had a follow-up about how results get presented.

00:46:52.120 --> 00:46:55.959
Do customers ever have access to Shiny apps?

00:46:55.959 --> 00:47:01.800
I guess I'll add or dash apps because I know using Python too, or Shiny for Python.

00:47:03.320 --> 00:47:11.399
Yeah, one of the really cool use cases around Shiny apps or like our Posit Connect platform

00:47:12.040 --> 00:47:21.239
is really in the area of like model transparency and like demystifying

00:47:21.239 --> 00:47:23.239
the black box of models a little bit.

00:47:23.239 --> 00:47:28.199
So one of our use cases is, you know, when we're working on a new model,

00:47:28.919 --> 00:47:31.560
our business partners have a lot of questions around,

00:47:31.560 --> 00:47:35.159
well, how would the model react if X?

00:47:35.159 --> 00:47:37.399
Or how would the model react if Y?

00:47:37.399 --> 00:47:41.080
Like how would the model react if we get a school lunch order

00:47:41.080 --> 00:47:43.639
and there's a hundred orders placed at one time?

00:47:43.639 --> 00:47:47.959
How would the model react if, you know, we had a snowstorm?

00:47:47.959 --> 00:47:50.280
Like what kind of labor would it recommend?

00:47:50.840 --> 00:47:53.560
Those types of questions.

00:47:53.560 --> 00:47:57.959
So what we've done is for some of our forecasting models,

00:47:57.959 --> 00:48:02.439
creating a Posit Connect application that just has that model on the backend

00:48:03.000 --> 00:48:06.760
and user inputs for the inputs for the model.

00:48:06.760 --> 00:48:10.199
So the user can go and experiment and do these what-if scenarios

00:48:10.199 --> 00:48:12.040
and see what the output would be.

00:48:12.040 --> 00:48:18.199
And that's really helped us achieve some comfortability with our partners.

00:48:18.199 --> 00:48:20.679
And I think it's a cool use case of that platform.

00:48:23.479 --> 00:48:24.520
Definitely. Thank you.

00:48:25.159 --> 00:48:25.659
Yeah.

00:48:27.000 --> 00:48:29.560
Azuka, and apologies for mispronouncing your name.

00:48:29.560 --> 00:48:31.719
I see you had a great question around advice

00:48:33.399 --> 00:48:35.959
for incoming or aspiring PhD students.

00:48:38.840 --> 00:48:39.879
Oh, yeah.

00:48:39.879 --> 00:48:43.000
Do you want to jump in and say hello?

00:48:45.959 --> 00:48:47.639
I can finish the rest of the question ones.

00:48:47.639 --> 00:48:51.719
But what advice do you have for incoming or aspiring PhD students

00:48:51.719 --> 00:48:55.959
in statistics that you wish you knew before you started your program?

00:48:58.040 --> 00:48:58.540
Man.

00:49:00.120 --> 00:49:00.600
Okay.

00:49:00.600 --> 00:49:05.479
There's two things I wish I could tell myself in my first year,

00:49:06.199 --> 00:49:09.639
you know, out of my PhD and into the industry.

00:49:11.639 --> 00:49:16.040
And one is, and I think it's related to another question we had today, but

00:49:17.639 --> 00:49:20.600
it's related to kind of this model accuracy, right?

00:49:20.600 --> 00:49:26.040
When you're in academia, like your objective is to find the best fitting model

00:49:26.040 --> 00:49:30.919
and to really look in order to move the field forward.

00:49:30.919 --> 00:49:33.479
That's where your focus needs to lie.

00:49:34.120 --> 00:49:37.959
Really, it is building that best model possible.

00:49:37.959 --> 00:49:43.560
But when you get into industry, the best model isn't necessarily the one

00:49:43.560 --> 00:49:47.399
that is going to be the most valuable, right?

00:49:47.399 --> 00:49:53.719
Maybe there's a simpler model that is more parsimonious.

00:49:53.719 --> 00:49:58.040
It's quicker to get out into production and start generating value.

00:49:58.040 --> 00:50:03.719
And there is a case to go with that simpler, quicker to deploy model

00:50:03.719 --> 00:50:07.320
than taking the time to do the full experimentation

00:50:07.320 --> 00:50:11.800
and really achieve the most optimal accuracy that's possible.

00:50:12.520 --> 00:50:17.879
So I had a few like scenarios where I was just taking too long to deliver

00:50:18.840 --> 00:50:22.360
because I was in this academic mindset of I needed to find the best solution.

00:50:23.000 --> 00:50:26.040
So, and not the most valuable solution.

00:50:26.040 --> 00:50:28.679
So that's one area.

00:50:29.560 --> 00:50:35.479
And then the other area is, you know, at least in my academic experience,

00:50:36.040 --> 00:50:41.800
like intellectual debate was really kind of something

00:50:41.800 --> 00:50:45.399
that you become second nature, right?

00:50:46.199 --> 00:50:49.479
You know, I really cherish the times in my PhD education

00:50:49.479 --> 00:50:54.199
where I got to, you know, challenge my classmates thinking and push back.

00:50:54.199 --> 00:50:59.560
And, you know, what came out of that is usually mutually beneficial

00:50:59.560 --> 00:51:00.439
to everyone involved.

00:51:02.040 --> 00:51:03.639
You can't do that in industry.

00:51:04.439 --> 00:51:08.520
Not everybody is really thinking that way.

00:51:08.520 --> 00:51:11.879
And really not everyone is expecting to join a meeting

00:51:11.879 --> 00:51:13.959
and be part of an academic debate.

00:51:13.959 --> 00:51:17.719
So, you know, that is one thing I learned early on is like,

00:51:17.719 --> 00:51:21.479
hey, why is everybody like, why does no one want to talk to me?

00:51:21.479 --> 00:51:25.320
And you can't challenge everyone's ideas all the time.

00:51:26.199 --> 00:51:30.919
So that's another lesson I wish I knew.

00:51:33.639 --> 00:51:34.120
Those are great.

00:51:34.120 --> 00:51:34.600
Thank you.

00:51:35.959 --> 00:51:38.600
Arati, I see you had a question on marketing campaigns.

00:51:38.600 --> 00:51:39.239
Want to jump in?

00:51:41.159 --> 00:51:41.659
Sure.

00:51:42.520 --> 00:51:44.360
Thank you so much for this today, Zach.

00:51:44.360 --> 00:51:46.840
This has been so helpful and interesting.

00:51:48.199 --> 00:51:51.959
I'm a marketing analyst, not in retail, but I was just curious,

00:51:51.959 --> 00:51:54.840
do you know what goes on behind your marketing campaigns?

00:51:54.840 --> 00:51:57.320
Like how they're targeted?

00:51:57.320 --> 00:52:00.840
Is it based on locations of customers and whatnot?

00:52:03.639 --> 00:52:04.139
Oh, boy.

00:52:07.479 --> 00:52:10.360
My kind of overlap with marketing is really only

00:52:10.360 --> 00:52:12.040
on the MLOps side, right?

00:52:13.320 --> 00:52:15.560
My substantive area of my team is more

00:52:15.560 --> 00:52:18.679
on the operations lens of things.

00:52:18.679 --> 00:52:21.399
But I work closely from an MLOps perspective

00:52:21.399 --> 00:52:25.239
with my counterparts in marketing.

00:52:25.239 --> 00:52:29.479
And wow, what a cool, hey, I didn't do a thumbs down.

00:52:31.399 --> 00:52:33.479
Bad AI, naughty AI.

00:52:34.040 --> 00:52:34.540
OK.

00:52:38.600 --> 00:52:40.679
The marketing department is really exciting.

00:52:41.320 --> 00:52:45.239
And the data scientists that work over there are great.

00:52:46.040 --> 00:52:48.840
Just like what a creative group.

00:52:49.479 --> 00:52:53.719
And the process of coming up with a new marketing campaign,

00:52:55.239 --> 00:52:57.080
the leaders over on the marketing side,

00:52:58.360 --> 00:53:01.159
they struck that balance of coming up

00:53:01.159 --> 00:53:04.040
with the creative ideas, but also partnering

00:53:04.040 --> 00:53:06.360
with our data science team to make sure

00:53:06.360 --> 00:53:09.800
that those ideas are viable and doing everything

00:53:09.800 --> 00:53:13.080
that we can before we release a campaign to understand

00:53:13.080 --> 00:53:14.360
what the impact is going to be.

00:53:15.159 --> 00:53:19.639
And fortunately, it's like a lot of things is on the upside.

00:53:19.639 --> 00:53:22.520
I don't know if you guys saw the emergency pizza campaign

00:53:22.520 --> 00:53:24.120
that we just launched, which said, hey,

00:53:24.120 --> 00:53:27.000
if you order a pizza, we'll give you a free emergency pizza

00:53:27.000 --> 00:53:28.120
whenever you need it.

00:53:28.120 --> 00:53:31.479
So part of the analysis was, how many people do we think

00:53:31.479 --> 00:53:32.760
are going to redeem this?

00:53:34.360 --> 00:53:37.719
Because we need to be prepared from a supply chain perspective

00:53:37.719 --> 00:53:39.479
and from an operations perspective,

00:53:39.479 --> 00:53:41.320
communicate to our franchisees that they need

00:53:41.320 --> 00:53:44.760
to have more people on the clock or order more dough

00:53:44.760 --> 00:53:47.239
because we're going to get so many emergency pizza orders.

00:53:48.760 --> 00:53:52.120
So it's a lot of that type of work.

00:53:52.120 --> 00:53:56.600
And I really think it's a bright star on our team

00:53:56.679 --> 00:53:59.159
is the partnership between data science and marketing.

00:53:59.159 --> 00:54:01.639
I think it's an industry leading partnership.

00:54:02.679 --> 00:54:03.080
Thank you.

00:54:06.120 --> 00:54:08.679
Curtis on our team is encouraging me to push back

00:54:08.679 --> 00:54:12.919
on the academic style debate one to say, well,

00:54:12.919 --> 00:54:15.560
how do we engage in good discussion

00:54:16.360 --> 00:54:19.320
if that academic style debate is sometimes less welcome?

00:54:20.760 --> 00:54:22.280
OK, ma'am.

00:54:23.320 --> 00:54:25.399
My PhD is in psychology.

00:54:25.399 --> 00:54:26.600
So you're going to get that.

00:54:27.959 --> 00:54:31.159
Sorry, but you asked the wrong person that question maybe

00:54:31.159 --> 00:54:31.959
or the right person.

00:54:31.959 --> 00:54:32.280
I don't know.

00:54:33.639 --> 00:54:36.919
So I think what's really important

00:54:36.919 --> 00:54:41.159
is to engage people on the emotional plane first.

00:54:43.239 --> 00:54:45.560
People have an emotional attachment to their work.

00:54:45.560 --> 00:54:46.520
It's what they spend.

00:54:48.040 --> 00:54:50.520
Most people, I would say, see the people that they work with

00:54:50.520 --> 00:54:53.800
more than they see their significant other sometimes.

00:54:54.760 --> 00:54:58.360
And the work that you do is such a huge part of your identity.

00:54:58.360 --> 00:55:00.199
And the projects that you work on at work

00:55:00.199 --> 00:55:01.879
are become a part of your identity.

00:55:02.439 --> 00:55:04.840
So when you're challenging someone's ideas,

00:55:04.840 --> 00:55:06.679
sometimes you're challenging their identity

00:55:06.679 --> 00:55:13.159
and the value that they view themselves.

00:55:13.159 --> 00:55:15.399
So really understanding that and meeting people

00:55:15.399 --> 00:55:17.639
on the emotional plane before you dive

00:55:17.639 --> 00:55:23.080
into the logical plane, I think, is a good strategy

00:55:23.080 --> 00:55:24.600
that I've tried to utilize.

00:55:24.600 --> 00:55:28.760
I'm not always perfect at it, but that's my pro tip.

00:55:31.719 --> 00:55:32.520
I love that.

00:55:32.520 --> 00:55:33.000
Thank you.

00:55:34.040 --> 00:55:37.320
So I guess that's inspiring me to ask the career question then

00:55:37.320 --> 00:55:40.760
because I'd love to get some more advice from you like that.

00:55:41.399 --> 00:55:43.320
Is there a piece of career advice

00:55:43.320 --> 00:55:45.399
that you've given to others on your team

00:55:45.399 --> 00:55:47.879
or that you've personally received

00:55:47.879 --> 00:55:49.080
that you'd like to share with us?

00:55:49.159 --> 00:55:49.659
Yeah.

00:55:51.479 --> 00:55:54.760
One of the best pieces of advice that I ever got from my mentor

00:55:55.399 --> 00:56:01.879
was you can't have everything all at once, right?

00:56:01.879 --> 00:56:05.639
You have yourself, your work, and your family.

00:56:06.360 --> 00:56:08.280
And when you're looking at your career

00:56:08.280 --> 00:56:13.159
and you're planning your career development,

00:56:13.159 --> 00:56:15.800
you need to look at it through the lens of your entire life

00:56:15.800 --> 00:56:18.199
and what it means in those other aspects of your life.

00:56:19.719 --> 00:56:21.320
Not just what it means for you at work.

00:56:22.840 --> 00:56:28.040
Maybe there's a time when, let's say, you have young kids

00:56:28.040 --> 00:56:31.479
and you need to pull back at work a little bit

00:56:31.479 --> 00:56:33.879
and put more of your energy into the family bucket.

00:56:36.040 --> 00:56:38.199
And it might not be like that forever.

00:56:38.199 --> 00:56:40.919
You might then decide after a certain amount of time,

00:56:40.919 --> 00:56:42.439
you're going to put more of yourself

00:56:42.439 --> 00:56:44.600
into your work bucket to advance your career.

00:56:45.239 --> 00:56:48.280
And looking at your career development,

00:56:48.760 --> 00:56:50.280
through the lens of your entire life,

00:56:51.239 --> 00:56:53.959
and how it impacts not just you, but the people around you,

00:56:53.959 --> 00:57:00.120
I think is the compass that I try to use

00:57:00.120 --> 00:57:01.399
when I'm thinking about my career.

00:57:05.959 --> 00:57:07.080
Thank you so much for that.

00:57:09.080 --> 00:57:12.280
I'm trying to scroll through and see if I missed any questions.

00:57:12.280 --> 00:57:14.199
I hate missing people's questions.

00:57:14.199 --> 00:57:16.760
So if you want to raise your hand here

00:57:16.840 --> 00:57:21.239
or feel free to re-copy and paste it into the chat

00:57:21.239 --> 00:57:22.040
so I can see it.

00:57:23.479 --> 00:57:27.320
But I think one more I see that I hadn't asked was,

00:57:27.320 --> 00:57:31.479
Azuka asked, is there anything unexpected in your current role

00:57:31.479 --> 00:57:33.560
that you haven't seen before

00:57:33.560 --> 00:57:36.679
or have experienced doing in your training?

00:57:36.679 --> 00:57:39.560
And how did you use your skill set to navigate that issue?

00:57:40.280 --> 00:57:43.000
And I'll copy the question over into the chat, too.

00:57:43.959 --> 00:57:46.040
I think the biggest challenge that I see,

00:57:47.320 --> 00:57:48.919
I know I've experienced this,

00:57:48.919 --> 00:57:52.600
and I see it in others as well,

00:57:52.600 --> 00:57:57.879
is if you're coming out of a technical background

00:57:57.879 --> 00:57:58.919
for your education,

00:57:59.560 --> 00:58:03.320
you don't get much exposure on how to lead people.

00:58:04.760 --> 00:58:08.360
And so I think that's a big challenge.

00:58:09.080 --> 00:58:11.800
And when you go from a technical role

00:58:11.800 --> 00:58:14.600
to a people leader role in the technical space,

00:58:16.199 --> 00:58:18.360
that's often a gap that I see is like,

00:58:19.959 --> 00:58:21.800
how do you motivate people?

00:58:21.800 --> 00:58:23.800
How do you have difficult conversations?

00:58:24.360 --> 00:58:28.679
How do you align people's skill set with their interests?

00:58:28.679 --> 00:58:30.439
Or is that even important?

00:58:31.719 --> 00:58:34.360
Those are the things that I often see that are missing.

00:58:35.000 --> 00:58:38.919
The technical stuff is usually not the challenge

00:58:38.919 --> 00:58:39.639
is what I've found.

00:58:43.080 --> 00:58:43.560
Thank you.

00:58:43.560 --> 00:58:45.879
Well, I know we're getting to the end of time here,

00:58:45.879 --> 00:58:47.399
but I do see your hand here, Rick.

00:58:47.399 --> 00:58:49.959
So I want to make sure we ask your question.

00:58:49.959 --> 00:58:51.239
Do you want to jump in?

00:58:51.239 --> 00:58:52.439
Well, thank you, Rachel.

00:58:52.439 --> 00:58:55.479
And Zach, you're an excellent example

00:58:55.479 --> 00:58:57.639
of a data science professional

00:58:57.639 --> 00:58:59.800
and a great representative of your company.

00:58:59.800 --> 00:59:01.719
Thank you for sharing your remarks.

00:59:01.719 --> 00:59:03.800
Quick question, with your focus,

00:59:03.800 --> 00:59:05.239
maybe it's your sub-teams,

00:59:05.239 --> 00:59:07.159
I'm a little unclear about that,

00:59:07.159 --> 00:59:11.320
but your focus on optimization and operations,

00:59:13.239 --> 00:59:15.479
do you make use of any IoT,

00:59:15.479 --> 00:59:19.159
Internet of Things devices for micro-optimizations?

00:59:19.879 --> 00:59:23.959
I'm aware in other settings where IoT devices

00:59:23.959 --> 00:59:26.360
have led to DS teams to discover

00:59:28.840 --> 00:59:31.080
tiny optimization opportunities,

00:59:31.080 --> 00:59:35.080
but then a million times a tiny optimization

00:59:35.080 --> 00:59:36.679
becomes a big optimization.

00:59:37.639 --> 00:59:39.959
Zach, your thoughts or experiences on this?

00:59:41.639 --> 00:59:42.139
Yeah.

00:59:43.320 --> 00:59:47.320
So we do have data points at that level, right?

00:59:47.320 --> 00:59:50.120
There are items in the store

00:59:50.840 --> 00:59:53.080
that employees kind of engage with

00:59:53.080 --> 00:59:55.719
that then end up as data points in our database.

00:59:55.719 --> 00:59:59.399
For example, when they clear the make line,

00:59:59.399 --> 01:00:00.919
like they made a pizza,

01:00:00.919 --> 01:00:02.120
before they put it in the oven,

01:00:02.120 --> 01:00:03.320
they have to click a button

01:00:03.320 --> 01:00:05.399
that says I'm done making this pizza.

01:00:05.399 --> 01:00:07.560
And that's like a really important data point for us

01:00:07.560 --> 01:00:09.959
because it helps us optimize points in the store.

01:00:11.719 --> 01:00:15.479
So I think to expand on this is like,

01:00:15.479 --> 01:00:16.919
of course we want more of that.

01:00:18.120 --> 01:00:20.360
Never ask a data scientist that they want more data

01:00:20.360 --> 01:00:21.719
because the answer is always yes.

01:00:22.600 --> 01:00:27.239
So I think we would love more data from IoT type devices,

01:00:27.239 --> 01:00:29.000
but we face two challenges there.

01:00:29.000 --> 01:00:31.080
One is cost, right?

01:00:31.080 --> 01:00:32.919
It's not like IoT in a factory

01:00:32.919 --> 01:00:38.040
where you might have like 200 different steps

01:00:38.040 --> 01:00:39.879
that you can kind of throw a device on

01:00:39.879 --> 01:00:41.080
and get a good pulse.

01:00:41.080 --> 01:00:43.560
We need to do that across 6,800 stores

01:00:43.560 --> 01:00:45.560
that are geographically dispersed

01:00:45.560 --> 01:00:47.639
literally everywhere in the country.

01:00:47.639 --> 01:00:51.080
So like getting those IoT devices in the store

01:00:51.080 --> 01:00:56.840
is a logistical challenge and a cost challenge, right?

01:00:56.840 --> 01:00:59.719
Because those devices are usually not cheap.

01:01:00.760 --> 01:01:03.879
Secondly, like our stores are franchise owned.

01:01:03.879 --> 01:01:05.800
So we would not only need to

01:01:08.439 --> 01:01:10.199
overcome those logistics and costs,

01:01:10.199 --> 01:01:12.760
but we need to convince franchisees

01:01:12.760 --> 01:01:15.639
that there's benefit in them doing that.

01:01:19.879 --> 01:01:23.000
Well, thank you so much, Zach, for joining us today.

01:01:23.000 --> 01:01:24.679
I've loved this discussion

01:01:24.679 --> 01:01:27.879
and thank you all for the great questions as well.

